{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141020062134|630340331","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Juan_Vargas","to":"Juan Vargas"}],"pages":{"2359039":{"pageid":2359039,"ns":0,"title":"Juan Vargas","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-11-13T15:15:40Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox State Senator \n| name            = Juan Vargas\n| image           = Juan Vargas official photo.jpg\n| state       = [[California]]\n| district     = [[California's 51st congressional district|51st]]\n| term_start   = January 3, 2013\n| preceded   = [[Bob Filner]]\n| state_senate2    = California State\n| district2        = [[California's 40th State Senate district|40th]]\n| term_start2      = December 6, 2010\n| term_end2        = January 2, 2013\n| preceded2        = [[Denise Moreno Ducheny]]\n| succeeded2       = [[Ben Hueso]]\n| state_assembly3 = California\n| district3       = [[California's 79th State Assembly district|79th]]\n| term_start3     = December 4, 2000\n| term_end3       = December 4, 2006\n| preceded3       = [[Denise Moreno Ducheny]]\n| succeeded3      = [[Mary Salas]]\n| office4         = Member of [[San Diego City Council]] from the Eighth District\n| term_start4     = February 22, 1993\n| term_end4       = December 4, 2000\n| preceded4       = [[Bob Filner]]\n| succeeded4      = [[Ralph Inzunza]]\n| nationality     = American\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1961|3|7}}\n| birth_place     = [[National City, California|National City]], [[California]]\n| residence       = [[San Diego, California|San Diego]], [[California]]\n| party           = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n| alma_mater      = [[Harvard Law School]]<br>[[Fordham University]]<br>[[University of San Diego]]\n| occupation      = [[lawyer|Attorney]]\n| religion        = [[Roman Catholic]]\n|spouse = Adrienne Vargas\n| children         = Rosa Celina<br> Helena Jeanne\n| website          = [http://vargas.house.gov/ Representative Juan Vargas] \n}}\n'''Juan C. Vargas''' (born March 7, 1961) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[California's 51st congressional district]] since 2013. The district includes all of [[Imperial County, California|Imperial County]] as well as the southernmost portions of [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wedrawthelines.ca.gov/downloads/meeting_handouts_082011/map_20110815_ap_cd_51_certified.pdf|title=District 51|date=August 2011|work=California Redistricting Commission certified map|publisher=Healthy City|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>  He is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]. \n\nVargas previously served in the [[California State Senate]] representing the 40th District, the [[California State Assembly]] representing the 79th district, and the [[San Diego City Council]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n{{refimprove|section|date=January 2013}}\nJuan Vargas was born on an egg ranch in [[National City, California]], where he grew up very poor. He is the third of ten children of Tomas and Celina Vargas, who immigrated to the United States from [[Mexico]] in the late 1940s as part of the Bracero program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vargas.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Full Biography|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Vargas graduated [[Latin honors|Magna Cum Laude]] with a BA from [[University of San Diego]] and earned an MA in Humanities from [[Fordham University]] in [[New York]].\n\nAfter college, Vargas joined the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] Novitiate (introduction) in [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]]. In the Jesuits, Vargas served in an orphanage in the civil-war-torn jungles of El Salvador. After leaving the Jesuits, he decided on law school and graduated in 1991 with a [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Harvard Law School]],<ref name = \"senate\" /> making him a classmate of President [[Barack Obama]].\n\n==Early political career (1992-2000)==\n===1992 congressional election===\n{{Seealso|United States House of Representatives elections, 1992}}\nIn 1992, he decided to run for the newly created [[California's 50th congressional district|50th Congressional District]], which was based in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]]. He lost the Democratic primary, ranking fourth with 19% of the vote. [[Bob Filner]] won the primary with a plurality of just 26%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207775|title=Our Campaigns - CA District 50 - D Primary Race - Jun 02, 1992|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> and went on to win the election.\n\n===San Diego City Council===\nVargas served on the [[San Diego City Council]] from 1993&ndash;2000. While on the Council, he created \"Operation Restore\" to employ [[Homelessness|homeless]] individuals to remove [[graffiti]] and to rehabilitate homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eastcountymagazine.org/node/11655|title=Meet Congressman Juan Vargas, who wins seat in 51st congressional district|last=Mork|first=Janis|date=November 7, 2012|work=East County Magazine|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===1996 congressional election===\nIn 1996, Vargas decided to challenge Filner in the Democratic primary. Vargas wouldn\u2019t debate Filner, so the incumbent instead sparred with a life-sized Vargas cardboard cutout. Vargas said he agrees with Filner on \u201c99 percent\u201d of issues.<ref>http://www.voiceofsandiego.org/government/article_4e6ac596-d848-11e1-91ca-001a4bcf887a.html</ref> Filner defeated him 55%-45%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=748257|title=Our Campaigns - CA District 50 - D Primary Race - Mar 26, 1996|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==California State Assembly (2000-2007)==\n===Elections===\nIn 2000, Vargas decided to run for [[California's 79th State Assembly district]]. He defeated Republican Jon Parungao 77%-19%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=210851|title=Our Campaigns - CA State Assembly 79 Race - Nov 07, 2000|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ut1\">{{cite web|url=http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/20060607-0052-7n7duke.html|title=Bilbray edges out Busby|last=LaVelle|first=Philip J.|author2=Dani Dodge|date=June 7, 2006|publisher=San Diego Union-Tribune|accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> In 2002, he defeated Republican Mark Fast 66%-30%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=5730|title=Our Campaigns - CA State Assembly 79 Race - Nov 05, 2002|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> In 2004, he defeated Libertarian Eli Wallace Conroe 85%-15%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=72949|title=Our Campaigns - CA State Assembly 79 Race - Nov 02, 2004|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn his first year in the Assembly, he was appointed Assistant Majority Leader. He authored AB 188, which was legislation that bans smoking in children's playgrounds. He also introduced legislation aimed at protecting children from [[Arcade games|arcade video games]]. Vargas also authored legislation to mandate life sentences for people who commit violent sex crimes against children, which served as a model for Chelsea\u2019s Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sd40.senate.ca.gov/biography|title=Biography|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Business and Professions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/news/techpolicy/2003-07-01-ca-spam-bills_x.htm|title=USATODAY.com - Consumer-backed bill fails; industry measure passes committee|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n*Insurance (Chair)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insurancejournal.com/news/newswire/west/2003/03/21/27316.htm|title=Calif. Commissioner Formally Enforces Regulatory Powers Over SCIF|date=21 March 2003|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2006 congressional election===\n{{Seealso|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2006#District 51}}\nIn 2006 Vargas decided to challenge Filner for a third time, this time in [[California's 51st congressional district]]. Vargas accused Filner of being a part of the [[Culture of corruption (2006)|culture of corruption]] of Washington, pointing out that Filner had paid his wife more than $500,000 in campaign funds for consulting services performed from their condominium in Washington. Filner in return argued that Vargas had controversial payments to his brother-in-law, who was a lobbyist for realtors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/bob-filner-ca/|title=Login|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.ivpressonline.com/2005-12-26/campaign-funds_24212116|title=Mudslinging, issues pit Vargas against Filner|work=Imperial Valley Press Online|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Filner defeated Vargas 51%-43%, with Danny Ramirez getting 6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=212958|title=Our Campaigns - CA District 51 - D Primary Race - Jun 06, 2006|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rawstory.com/news/2006/Bigamy_bribery_other_allegations_plague_congressional_0605.html|title=Bigamy, bribery, other allegations plague California congressional race|last=Raftery|first=Miriam|date=June 5, 2006|publisher=The Raw Story|accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"ut1\" /> \n==Business career (2007-2009)==\nAfter leaving the State Assembly in 2006 due to term limits, Vargas took a job with a home, auto and small business insurance company and was tasked with creating jobs and outreach in diverse San Diego Communities as part of the company's diversity initiative.{{citation needed|date=February 2011}} Vargas left his job at the end of 2009 to return to public service as a Democratic candidate for the California State Senate.\n\n==California State Senate (2010-2013)==\n===2010 election===\nIn 2010 Vargas narrowly won a seat in the California State Senate, 40th District.  He defeated Assemblywoman [[Mary Salas]] by 22 votes, after recounts in San Diego and Riverside counties. He resigned from the Senate effective January 2, 2013 so that he could take his seat as a Congressman. A special election to fill his seat was held in March 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Peters, Vargas ready for Washington fray|last=Walker|first=Mark|date=January 3, 2013|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n;Standing Committees\n*Banking & Financial Institutions (Chair)\n*Agriculture\n*Business, Professions, and Economic Development\n*Education\n*Public Employment and Retirement\n\n;Subcommittee\n*Education: Sustainable School Facilities\n\n;Joint Committee\n*Rules<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sd40.senate.ca.gov/|title=Home - Senator|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Select Committee\n*Recovery, Reform, and Re-Alignment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votevargas.com/about.php|title=Juan Vargas, Democrat for United States Congress|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2012-Present)==\n===2012 election===\nIn 2012 when Filner announced he would retire from Congress to run for [[Mayor of San Diego]], Vargas endorsed him despite their history of bitter rivalry.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Politics of Bob Filner\u2019s Personality |author=Liam Dillon |url=http://www.voiceofsandiego.org/government/article_4e6ac596-d848-11e1-91ca-001a4bcf887a.html |newspaper=Voice of San Diego |date=2 November 2012 |accessdate=26 January 2013 |quote=Last summer, Juan Vargas walked up to Filner in a beer line at a South Bay festival with a message he\u2019s never given Filner before. Vargas told Filner he was going to endorse him. }}</ref> Vargas then ran for Filner's seat in the [[California's 51st congressional district|51st district]]. In the open primary, he ranked first with 46% of the vote. Republican Michael Crimmins ranked second with 20%, Democrat State Senator [[Denise Moreno Ducheny]] came in third with 15%, and four other candidates received single digit percentages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=735348|title=Our Campaigns - CA - District 51 - Open Primary Race - Jun 05, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> In November, he defeated Crimmins 71%-29%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=768473|title=Our Campaigns - CA - District 51 Race - Nov 06, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-general/12-us-reps.pdf|title=Presidential General Election, Tuesday, November 5, 2012|work=United States Representative|publisher=California Secretary of State|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> \n\n===Tenure===\nHe was sworn in on January 3, 2013. \n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Horticulture, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia|Subcommittee on the Middle East and South Asia]]\n**[[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on House Administration|Committee on House Administration]]'''\n\n==Personal life==\nHe and his wife Adrienne live in the [[Golden Hill, San Diego|Golden Hill]] area of San Diego and have two daughters. During the 1999 [[Kosovo War|armed conflict]] in Kosovo, Vargas welcomed a Kosovar refugee family into his family's home for nearly two years.<ref name = \"senate\">{{cite web|url=http://sd40.senate.ca.gov/biography|title=Senator Juan Vargas: California Senate District 40|work=California State Senate|accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vargas.house.gov/ Congressman Juan Vargas] official U.S. House website\n*[http://votevargas.com/ Juan Vargas for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Juan_Vargas_%5BD-51%5D|Juan Vargas}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = V000130 | ballot = Juan_Vargas | nndb = | votesmart = 29100 | govtrack = 412522 | opencong = 412522 | rollcall = 1606 | politifact = | fec = H2CA50026 | opensecrets = N00007021 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = 4427 | ontheissues = CA/Juan_Vargas.htm | congress = juan-vargas/2112 | worldcat = | c-span = juanvargas | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = ec1c449e-4bbc-11e2-8758-b64a2997a921 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=California\n| district=51\n| before=[[Bob Filner]]\n| years=January 3, 2013-Present\n| after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Valadao]]<br><small>R-[[California]]}}\n{{s-t